07312nam a22011655i 9783110892222DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20112006gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831108922227 a10.1515/97831108922222doi  a(DE-B1597)42251  a(OCoLC)979883488  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP380b.P73 2006eb 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.44094222  aES 4402rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27840:00aEurotyp :bTypology of Languages in Europe. n8, pPragmatic Organization of Discourse in the Languages of Europe /ced. by Giuliano Bernini, Marcia L. Schwartz.  aReprint 2012 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2011] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (632 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEmpirical Approaches to Language Typology [EALT] ,x0933-761X ;v20-800ti-iv -- tGeneral Preface -- tContents -- tContents detailed -- tContributors -- tI. General issue -- tIntroduction -- tSpoken and written language -- tII. From function to form -- tSentence topics in the languages of Europe and beyond -- tFocus in the languages of Europe -- tDeixis and anaphora: Some case studies -- tTheticity -- tIII. From form to function -- tThe de-accenting of given information: A cognitive universal? -- tInteraction of syntactic and pragmatic factors on basic word order in the languages of Europe -- tArticles and article systems in some areas of Europe -- tSubject index. Language index. Author index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe volume is a collection of papers reporting the results of investigations on the interaction of discourse and sentence structure in the languages of Europe. The subjects discussed in the book include: morphosyntactic characteristics of spontaneous spoken texts; different patterns of word order in a pragmatic perspective; the coding of the pragmatic functions topic and focus in sentences with non-canonical word orders (e.g. dislocations, clefts); the range of functions of verb-subject order in declarative clauses and the notion of theticity; prosodic patterns of de-accenting of given information; deixis and anaphora; coding of definiteness and article systems. The book provides the empirical basis for the comparative survey of major phenomena found in the languages of Europe which have pragmatic relevance. Beside traditional areas of investigation at the interface between syntax and pragmatics such as dislocations, new areas are explored, such as the prosody of given information. Data are considered within a functional-typological approach.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDiscourse analysis. 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxSyntax. 0aPragmatics. 4aDiskursanalyse. 4aEuropa /Sprache. 4aEurope /language. 4aSprachtypologie. 4adiscourse analysis. 4alinguistic typology. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aEurope/language.  adiscourse analysis.  alinguistic typology.  apragmatics.1 aBernini, Giuliano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernini, Giuliano, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBolkestein, A. Machtelt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruttenden, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFernandez-Vest, M. M. Jocelyne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKönig, Ekkehard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaslova, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatras, Yaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re